Corona information

Authorities are providing information on the spread of the coronavirus disease (COVID-19). You should follow the instructions given by authorities to slow down the spread of the virus and to protect risk groups, such as older people. You can also download Koronavilkku to your smartphone.

You can find information and instructions on the THL's and Finnish goverment's websites.

See health centres on a Suomi.fi Map. 


More information and services related to the financial difficulties of companies are gathered to our company section.

  • First, you can make a symptom assessment in the Omaolo online service (only in Finnish or Swedish).

    If your symptoms are mild and you do not belong to any risk group, see the Finnish Institute for Health and Welfare website for more detailed instructions (only in Finnish).

    Do not go to pharmacy if you have a flu. You can authorise someone else to act on your behalf in a pharmacy using the Suomi.fi e-authorizations.

  • Read about seeking treatment on the Finnish Institute for Health and Welfare website (only in Finnish).

    Call your health centre before seeking treatment.

  • You are recommended to wear a mask when you

    • travel on public transport
    • are on your way to a coronavirus test and are waiting for the test result
    • return to Finland from a high-risk area.

    You can also wear a face mask in other situations if it is not possible to keep a safe distance to other people. The recomendation to wear a face mask may vary between the areas of Finland.

    For more specific instructions for using a mask, read the recomendation of the THL.

  • You can find more information about coronavirus on the Finnish Institute for Health and Welfare website.

    Explore also Finnish goverment's website.

    You can use the Korona-info chat feature to ask for general information about coronavirus.

    You can also call the helpline providing information about coronavirus.

  • If you are ordered to be absent from work due to coronavirus, Kela may pay you sickness allowance on account of an infectious disease.

  • If you become ill and are unable to work for more than two weeks, you have a right to sickness allowance paid by Kela.

  • If you become unemployed or if you are laid off, you can find information on the Suomi.fi website.

    It is also worth checking your rights during your layoff.

    In the event that your employer has filed for bankruptcy or has other difficulties paying salaries, you can get outstanding wages from pay security. 

  • If your income and assets do not cover your essential daily expenses, you may be entitled to basic social assistance.

    Kela offers more detailed information about the impacts of the coronavirus situation on various forms of social assistance and benefits.
